t1937.text: Do you want to know the cherry on top of the shit Sundae? My phone’s charging port decided that now would be the perfect time to shit itself. Hello universe, are you quite done messing with me? What did I do to you? Can we stop this now?

t1938.text: Oh and I can’t even get hold of my coordinator because she only works a few days a week. Just my luck that they call right before her days off. Why? Why must it be this way?

t1939.text: Her report was extremely specific so she doesn’t understand why they’re giving us so much grief. It now looks like we’ll have to jump through hoops of fire to get it. Shower chairs are classed as low risk so it should never have been this difficult.

t1940.text: I think I’m more disabled by my chronic pain but this particular person doesn’t think it’s relevant. It’s not related to my blindness so she doesn’t want a bar of it. anyway, I finally get off the phone and tell my OT about the conversation. She. Is. Pissed. Really really pissed.

t1941.text: When you have multiple disabilities, they interact in ways that wouldn’t happen if you only had one. The NDIA have decided my primary disability is my blindness but I don’t think so. It can be disabling, however, I was born like that so I’m used to it.

t1942.text: The person on the phone changed her story yet again. She tried to say it wouldn’t get funded because it had nothing to do with my blindness. And here we go again with this ridiculous notion of a primary disability. I cannot stress this enough. This. Is. Not. A. Thing.

t1943.text: I’m going to sound like a broken record but again, I knew that was BS. I had to fish through the archives but I did eventually find the relevant Report. It was extremely thorough and everyone else who Reddit thought so too.

t1944.text: I’ve asked to be copied into all correspondence about my case and now I’m bloody glad I did. I knew what she was saying wasn’t right and I had proof to back it up. She backtracked and tried to claim that, although they had the report, it wasn’t thorough enough.

t1945.text: She tried claiming that my OT had never written a report explaining why I needed a shower chair. I know she did because I read said report. I also know it went where it was supposed to go because my coordinator copied me in to her email.

t1946.text: Oh but hold on, it gets worse. That’s not the only way the person on the phone was being a right nuisance. We were discussing funding and she was asking me what needed to be increased. I told her I needed funding for a shower chair and she reckoned that could never happen..

t1947.text: How the blistering blue blazes can we be independent when you won’t even make your content accessible to us? Seriously! Tell us because I have no idea. And I’m getting sidetracked again. Onwards.

t1948.text: I shouldn’t have to do this. Also, I don’t have support every day so my mail doesn’t always get checked. What if I missed an important letter from them? They go on and on about independence and yet they do stuff like this.

t1949.text: She then went on to say: “we assume that people who get funding from us have people to read their mail for them.” What if I don’t want to? What if I want to read my own bloody mail for once in my life?

t1950.text: She says that she’s just following protocol. So? I don’t see why you can’t send it in braille or some other format. You’ve done it before. You’re the National disability insurance agency for crying out loud! I didn’t say that to her but I wanted to.

t1951.text: Do humans deserve to be dealt this pandemic?

t1952.text: The person who called me was, to put it bluntly, A right twit. She said she would send a letter when the final decision has been reached. I asked her if she could send it in a more accessible format and that went down like a lead balloon.

t1953.text: They don’t see what affect their decisions have. I feel like we are nothing to them but a bunch of case files waiting for inspection. Anyway, I’m getting sidetracked. I could go on about that for yonks.

t1954.text: Said delegate decides whether or not I get more funding. All the relevant information is collected and passed along to them. I really don’t like that because I never get to speak to the person who makes The final decision.

t1955.text: I was beginning to wonder whether a review would ever actually happen. As time went on, my hopes decreased but here we are. They rang and said that my case was finally being looked at. The person I spoke to said she would put the information together and give it to a delegate.

t1956.text: I have had a frig of a day. My NDIS plan is getting reviewed and the whole process is a pain in the arse. I applied for a review in August last year and it’s only just now reached their office. About bloody time!
